    <h2>IBM Cloud Watson Studio</h2>
    <p>Estimated Time (45 min)</p>
    <p>IBM Watson Studio is a service from IBM, that provides a suite of to=
ols and a collaborative environment for data scientists, developers and dom=
ain experts. In this lab, you will use Watson Studio and explore different =
datasets. As we have learnt in the course, the data is not only about numbe=
rs, it can be anything such as numeric data, text data, images, videos, aud=
ios etc. You will work on three samples.</p>
    <p><strong>Sample 1</strong> in which you will learn about the dataset =
in which only numeric attributes are present.</p>
    <p><strong>Sample 2</strong> in which you will learn about the dataset =
in which numeric &amp; text attributes are present.</p>
    <p><strong>Sample 3</strong> in which you will analyze how the Jupyter =
Notebooks look like. How a Data Scientist create the models?</p>
    <p>Let's take a look that how different datasets are used by Data Scien=
tist.</p>
    <h4>Objectives :</h4>
    <p>You will learn to:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Launch Watson Studio for accessing Data Science Problems</li>
      <li>Evaluate Numeric dataset</li>
      <li>Evaluate dataset with Non-Numeric attributes</li>
      <li>Evaluate Jupyter Notebook</li>
    </ul>

low the instructions given in the <a href=3D"https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.=
cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-DS0101EN-Ski=
llsNetwork/labs/Module%202/IBM_Cloud_Account_Setup.md.html" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"external">link</a></p>

    <h5>Explore the data</h5>
    <p>The data is related to forest fires where the aim is to predict the =
burned area of forest fires, in the northeast region of Portugal, by using =
meterological and other data.</p>
    <p><strong>Attribute Information:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>X - x-axis spatial coordinate within the Montesinho park map: 1 t=
o 9</li>
      <li>Y - y-axis spatial coordinate within the Montesinho park map: 2 t=
o 9</li>
      <li>month - month of the year: 'jan' to 'dec'</li>
      <li>day - day of the week: 'mon' to 'sun'</li>
      <li>FFMC - FFMC index from the FWI system: 18.7 to 96.20</li>
      <li>DMC - DMC index from the FWI system: 1.1 to 291.3</li>
      <li>DC - DC index from the FWI system: 7.9 to 860.6</li>
      <li>ISI - ISI index from the FWI system: 0.0 to 56.10</li>
      <li>temp - temperature in Celsius degrees: 2.2 to 33.30</li>
      <li>RH - relative humidity in %: 15.0 to 100</li>
      <li>wind - wind speed in km/h: 0.40 to 9.40</li>
      <li>rain - outside rain in mm/m2 : 0.0 to 6.4</li>
      <li>area - the burned area of the forest (in ha): 0.00 to 1090.84</li=
>
    </ol>
    <p>
      (this output variable is very skewed towards 0.0, thus it may make
      sense to model with the logarithm transform).
    </p>
    <h3>Exercise 2: Evaluate Non-Numeric dataset</h3>
    <p>The data doesn't have to be only based on numbers. Data can be text,=
 images and other types as well. Let's look into data having text values.</=
p>
    <ol>
      <li>Use the <em>All Filters</em>. From <em>Format</em> select <em>Dat=
a</em> and from <em>Topic</em> select <em>Economy and Business</em>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>You will get mutiple datasets given. Scroll down and select <em>Airb=
nb Data for Analytics: Trentino Reviews</em> (If you will not get the data =
using <strong>Load More</strong> option)</p>

    <h5>Explore the data</h5>
    <p>Airbnb, Inc. is an American company that operates an online marketpl=
ace for lodging, primarily homestays for vacation rentals, and tourism acti=
vities. Airbnb guests may leave a review after their stay, and these can be=
 used as an indicator of airbnb activity.The minimum stay, price and number=
 of reviews have been used to estimate the occupancy rate, the number of ni=
ghts per year and the income per month for each listing.</p>
    <p>This data can be used in various ways - To analyze the star ratings =
of places, to analyze the location preferences of the customers, to analyze=
 the tone and sentiment of customer reviews and many more. Airbnb uses loca=
tion data to improve guest satisfaction.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>=F0=9F=92=A1 Can you think of what you can use this data for?</p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>The dataset comprises of three main tables:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>listings - Detailed listings data showing 96 attributes for each=
 of the listings. Some of the attributes used in the analysis are price(con=
tinuous), longitude (continuous), latitude (continuous), listing_type (cate=
gorical), is_superhost (categorical), neighbourhood (categorical), ratings =
(continuous) among others.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>reviews - Detailed reviews given by the guests with 6 attributes=
. Key attributes include date (datetime), listing_id (discrete), reviewer_i=
d (discrete) and comment (textual).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>calendar - Provides details about booking for the next year by l=
isting. Four attributes in total including listing_id (discrete), date(date=
time), available (categorical) and price (continuous).</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Exercise 3: Evaluate Jupyter Notebook</h3>
    <p>Use the <em>All Filters</em>. From <em>Format</em> select <em>Notebo=
ok</em> and select <em>Finding optimal locations of new stores using Decisi=
on Optimization</em></p>
    <img src=3D"https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomai=
n.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-DS0101EN-SkillsNetwork/labs/Module%202/im=
ages/New_Store.png" style=3D"border: solid 1px grey;margin-top: 30px; margi=
n-left: 30px; margin-bottom: 30px">
    <p>This notebook shows you how Decision Optimization can help to prescr=
ibe decisions for a complex constrained problem using Python to help determ=
ine the optimal location for a new store.</p>
    <p>The objective is to minimize the total distance from libraries to co=
ffee shops so that a book reader always gets to our coffee shop easily. It =
can be done by analyzing and displaying the location of the coffee shops on=
 a map.</p>
    <img src=3D"https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomai=
n.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-DS0101EN-SkillsNetwork/labs/Module%202/im=
ages/Notebook.png" style=3D"border: solid 1px grey;margin-top: 30px; margin=
-left: 30px; margin-bottom: 30px">
    <p>When we validate the dataset, the locations on map are seperated.</p=
>
    <img src=3D"https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomai=
n.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-DS0101EN-SkillsNetwork/labs/Module%202/im=
ages/loc_jupyter.png" style=3D"border: solid 1px grey;margin-top: 30px; mar=
gin-left: 30px; margin-bottom: 30px">
    <p>But it is impossible to determine where to ideally open the coffee s=
hops by just looking at the map.</p>
    <p>This is solved by an optimization model that will help us determine =
where to locate the coffee shops in an optimal way.</p>
    <img src=3D"https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomai=
n.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-DS0101EN-SkillsNetwork/labs/Module%202/im=
ages/loc2_jupyter.png" style=3D"border: solid 1px grey;margin-top: 30px; ma=
rgin-left: 30px; margin-bottom: 30px">
    <h4>Summary</h4>
    <p>In this lab, you have learnt about how different datasets are availa=
ble and how a data scientist create and predict the models using the model =
building in IBM Watson Jupyter Notebook.</p>
